    "shortDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma of unspecified part of face",
    "longDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma of unspecified part of face",
    "plainEnglish": "Merkel cell carcinoma is a rare and aggressive form of skin cancer that develops from neuroendocrine cells in the skin, typically appearing as a firm, painless nodule on the face. This cancer grows quickly and has a high risk of spreading to other parts of the body, making early detection and treatment crucial. The \"unspecified part of face\" designation means the exact location on the face hasn't been more precisely documented.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and surgical specialists use this code when diagnosing and treating Merkel cell carcinoma of the face. It commonly appears in medical records, oncology treatment plans, and insurance EOB statements, as this diagnosis typically requires significant medical intervention including surgery and sometimes chemotherapy or radiation therapy.",
