    "longDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma of other parts of face",
    "plainEnglish": "Merkel cell carcinoma is a rare and aggressive skin cancer that develops from special nerve cells in the skin called Merkel cells, located in areas of the face other than the eyelid, nose, or ear. These tumors typically appear as a firm, painless nodule that may be flesh-colored, red, or blue, and they grow quickly and have a high risk of spreading to other parts of the body. The exact cause isn't fully understood, but risk factors include sun exposure, a weakened immune system, and infection with Merkel cell polyomavirus.",
