    "longDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma of overlapping sites",
    "plainEnglish": "Merkel cell carcinoma is a rare but aggressive skin cancer that develops from neuroendocrine cells in the skin, typically appearing as a firm, painless nodule that may be red, purple, or skin-colored. When this cancer affects multiple overlapping areas of the body rather than being confined to one location, it indicates more widespread disease and typically requires more aggressive treatment. This type of cancer grows quickly and has a higher risk of spreading to lymph nodes and other parts of the body compared to other skin cancers.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, dermatologists, and surgical oncologists use this code when documenting Merkel cell carcinoma that involves multiple adjacent or overlapping body sites. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, radiation, surgical removal, or immunotherapy for this aggressive skin cancer, as treatment often involves multidisciplinary care.",
