    "rawCode": "C4A9",
    "shortDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Merkel cell carcinoma, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Merkel cell carcinoma is a rare and aggressive skin cancer that develops from neuroendocrine cells in the skin, typically appearing as a firm, painless nodule or bump that often has a reddish or purple color. It tends to grow quickly and can spread to lymph nodes and other parts of the body, and while the exact cause isn't fully understood, it's associated with sun exposure, immunosuppression, and a virus called Merkel cell polyomavirus. The 'unspecified' designation means the doctor has identified this cancer but hasn't documented which specific area of the skin it's located on.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists and oncologists primarily use this code when diagnosing and treating Merkel cell carcinoma, often in collaboration with surgical specialists and pathologists who confirm the diagnosis through biopsy. This code frequently appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing skin biopsies, surgical removal, staging workups, and cancer treatment, as Merkel cell carcinoma requires aggressive management and close monitoring.",
