    "shortDesc": "Unspecified malignant neoplasm of skin of nose",
    "longDesc": "Unspecified malignant neoplasm of skin of nose",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer of the skin on or around the nose where doctors haven't yet determined the specific type of cancer cell involved. Skin cancer can develop from sun exposure, age, or other risk factors, and may appear as an unusual bump, sore, or discolored patch on the nose that doesn't heal. The exact cell type (like melanoma or squamous cell carcinoma) would need to be identified through biopsy or pathology to be more specific.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and general practitioners use this code when documenting a newly diagnosed or unspecified malignant skin tumor on the nose. It commonly appears on EOB statements during initial cancer diagnosis and workup, though it is typically replaced with a more specific code once pathology results identify the exact cancer type.",
