    "rawCode": "C44310",
    "shortDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin of unspecified parts of face",
    "longDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin of unspecified parts of face",
    "plainEnglish": "Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, starting in the basal cells at the bottom layer of the epidermis (outer skin layer). When it develops on the face, it often appears as a shiny, pearly bump or a scaly, reddish patch that may bleed or not heal properly. This code specifically indicates the cancer is on the face but the exact location hasn't been specified.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and surgical specialists use this code when diagnosing and treating facial skin cancers. It frequently appears on patient EOB statements because basal cell carcinoma of the face is very common and is often treated with procedures like excision, Mohs surgery, or other removal techniques in an outpatient setting.",
