    "shortDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin of other parts of face",
    "longDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin of other parts of face",
    "plainEnglish": "Basal cell carcinoma is a type of skin cancer that develops in the basal cells (the deepest layer of the epidermis) on areas of the face other than the eyelid, nose, or lip. It typically appears as a small, waxy bump, scaly patch, or open sore that may bleed or crust over, and is usually caused by excessive sun exposure over time. This is the most common type of skin cancer and, while it can be disfiguring if left untreated, it rarely spreads to other parts of the body.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists and general practitioners diagnose and treat basal cell carcinoma, often using biopsy confirmation. This code appears on patient EOB statements for office visits, biopsies, Mohs surgery, cryotherapy, or other removal procedures, and is commonly seen in oncology billing and reconstructive surgery consultations.",
