    "plainEnglish": "This is a type of skin cancer called squamous cell carcinoma that has developed on the nose. Squamous cell carcinoma starts in the flat cells on the surface of the skin and is usually caused by prolonged sun exposure over many years. You might notice a scaly, crusty, or bleeding bump or sore on your nose that doesn't heal, or it could look like a flat, firm, reddish patch.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and otolaryngologists (ear, nose, and throat specialists) use this code when diagnosing and treating skin cancer on the nose. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when biopsies confirm squamous cell carcinoma and treatment such as surgery, radiation, or chemotherapy is planned or performed.",
