    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a type of skin cancer called squamous cell carcinoma that has developed on the torso (trunk) of the body, excluding the back, breast, and abdomen—typically on areas like the sides, shoulders, or upper chest. Squamous cell carcinoma grows from the flat cells in the outer layer of skin and is usually caused by prolonged sun exposure; it typically appears as a firm, scaly bump or sore that may bleed or not heal properly.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and general surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating skin cancers. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements when a skin biopsy confirms squamous cell carcinoma and treatment is planned, as it helps insurers understand the specific location and type of cancer for coverage and billing purposes.",
