    "longDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of overlapping sites of skin",
    "plainEnglish": "This is a type of skin cancer called basal cell carcinoma that involves two or more areas of the skin that are next to each other or overlap in location. Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer and usually develops from sun damage to the skin, appearing as a persistent bump, sore, or scaly patch that doesn't heal. It grows slowly and rarely spreads to other parts of the body, but needs to be removed or treated by a doctor to prevent it from growing deeper into the skin.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists and general practitioners commonly diagnose and treat this condition, while surgical oncologists or Mohs surgeons may perform specialized removal procedures. This code regularly appears on patient EOB statements as it represents a relatively common skin cancer diagnosis requiring medical intervention and pathology confirmation.",
