    "shortDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin, unspecified",
    "longDesc": "Basal cell carcinoma of skin, unspecified",
    "plainEnglish": "Basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer, starting in the deepest layer of your epidermis (the basal cells). It typically appears as a slow-growing bump, sore, or scaly patch on sun-exposed skin that doesn't heal, and this code is used when doctors haven't specified exactly which part of the body is affected. This cancer is almost always caused by sun exposure and grows very slowly, rarely spreading to other parts of the body, though it does need to be removed to prevent it from damaging surrounding skin and tissue.",
    "whoUses": "Dermatologists, oncologists, and primary care physicians use this code when diagnosing and treating skin cancer. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements as an outpatient diagnosis code for skin biopsies, evaluations, and treatment visits, and is frequently the starting point before a more specific anatomical location code is assigned once the lesion site is documented.",
