    "plainEnglish": "Mesothelioma is a rare and aggressive cancer that develops in the thin layer of tissue covering most internal organs, usually caused by inhaling asbestos fibers over many years. The disease typically starts in the lungs or abdomen and can take 20-50 years to develop after asbestos exposure, causing symptoms like chest pain, persistent coughing, shortness of breath, or abdominal swelling. When doctors use the code \"unspecified,\" it means they've diagnosed mesothelioma but haven't yet determined exactly which type or location it is.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, pulmonologists, and thoracic surgeons primarily use this code when initially diagnosing or documenting mesothelioma cases. It commonly appears on patient EOB statements during cancer workup and treatment phases, though it's often updated to a more specific subtype (pleural, peritoneal, or pericardial) once imaging and biopsies are completed.",
