    "shortDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of esophagus",
    "longDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of esophagus",
    "plainEnglish": "A gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is a rare type of cancer that starts in the connective tissue cells of the esophagus (the tube that carries food from your mouth to your stomach). These tumors grow from specialized nerve cells in the esophagus wall and can range from slow-growing to aggressive, potentially causing difficulty swallowing, chest pain, or bleeding.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical specialists use this code when diagnosing and treating esophageal GISTs. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging, endoscopy, biopsy, surgery, or targeted cancer therapy, as GISTs are typically treated with specialized medications like imatinib (Gleevec).",
