    "rawCode": "C49A2",
    "shortDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of stomach",
    "longDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of stomach",
    "plainEnglish": "A gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) of the stomach is a rare cancer that develops in the connective tissue cells (called interstitial cells of Cajal) that line the stomach wall. These tumors can grow slowly or rapidly and may cause symptoms like abdominal pain, bloating, or internal bleeding. Most GISTs are caused by mutations in specific genes (KIT or PDGFRA) that make the cells grow uncontrollably.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical oncologists use this code when diagnosing and treating stomach GISTs. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging, biopsies, surgery, or targeted therapy (like imatinib), as GISTs are increasingly recognized and tracked for insurance and treatment planning purposes.",
