    "rawCode": "C49A3",
    "shortDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of small intestine",
    "longDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of small intestine",
    "plainEnglish": "A gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is a rare cancer that develops in the small intestine, usually starting in the specialized nerve cells that control digestive muscle contractions. These tumors can vary widely in how aggressive they are—some grow slowly and cause minimal symptoms, while others grow faster and may cause abdominal pain, bleeding, or digestive problems. The exact cause isn't fully understood, but most GISTs are caused by mutations in specific genes (KIT or PDGFRA) that make cells grow uncontrollably.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical oncologists use this code when diagnosing and treating small intestine GISTs. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging, biopsy, surgery, or targeted cancer therapy (like imatinib), and is typically associated with significant treatment costs and specialist consultations.",
