    "shortDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of large intestine",
    "longDesc": "Gastrointestinal stromal tumor of large intestine",
    "plainEnglish": "A gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) of the large intestine is a rare type of cancer that grows in the muscle or connective tissue layer of the colon. These tumors develop from specialized nerve cells in the bowel wall and can range from slow-growing to aggressive, sometimes causing bleeding, abdominal pain, or changes in bowel habits. Unlike most colon cancers, GISTs are not related to typical colon cancer risk factors like polyps or family history.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical oncologists diagnose and treat GISTs using endoscopy, imaging, and surgical removal. This code appears on EOB statements when patients are being evaluated for or treated for GIST, particularly in oncology or specialized gastrointestinal cancer centers, though it is relatively uncommon compared to other colorectal cancers.",
