    "plainEnglish": "A gastrointestinal stromal tumor (GIST) is a rare cancer that grows in the connective tissue of the digestive system, in this case in unusual locations not specifically identified elsewhere. These tumors arise from specialized nerve cells (called interstitial cells of Cajal) in the stomach, small intestine, or other areas of the digestive tract. Symptoms can include abdominal pain, bleeding, or a palpable mass, though some people may have no symptoms until the tumor grows larger.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical oncologists use this code when diagnosing and treating GISTs in atypical locations. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing imaging, biopsies, surgery, or targeted chemotherapy (such as imatinib), as GISTs require specialized cancer treatment planning.",
