    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that has developed in the axillary tail of a man's left breast—the breast tissue that extends into the armpit area. The axillary tail is the uppermost outer portion of breast tissue, and cancer in this location may be detected as a lump, swelling, or other changes in that area. Men can develop breast cancer just like women, though it's less common, and this code specifically identifies that the cancer is in the left breast's outer/armpit region.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, surgical oncologists, and general surgeons use this code when diagnosing and treating male breast cancer. It commonly appears in hospital records, pathology reports, and treatment summaries, though it's relatively uncommon on patient EOBs compared to female breast cancer codes since male breast cancer represents only about 1% of all breast cancers.",
