    "plainEnglish": "Inflammatory breast cancer (IBC) is a rare but aggressive type of breast cancer that starts in the right breast and causes swelling, redness, and dimpling of the skin, making it look like an orange peel or infected area. Unlike other breast cancers, it develops quickly and spreads to other parts of the body, and patients typically notice visible skin changes rather than a lump. The cancer cells block lymph vessels in the skin, which is what causes the inflammatory appearance and rapid progression.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists (cancer specialists), breast surgeons, and pathologists use this code when diagnosing and treating inflammatory breast cancer. This code commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, radiation, or surgical treatment, as IBC requires aggressive multimodal therapy and frequent specialist consultations.",
    "billable": true,
