    "code": "C69.52",
    "rawCode": "C6952",
    "shortDesc": "Malignant neoplasm of left lacrimal gland and duct",
    "longDesc": "Malignant neoplasm of left lacrimal gland and duct",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that has developed in the lacrimal gland on the left side of your eye—the small gland responsible for producing tears. This type of cancer is relatively rare and can cause symptoms like persistent eye irritation, a lump or swelling near the inner corner of your eye, or excessive tearing. The cancer may grow slowly or more aggressively depending on its type and stage.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, ophthalmologists, and otolaryngologists (ENT specialists) use this code when diagnosing and treating lacrimal gland cancers. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or surgical removal of the gland, as lacrimal gland malignancies are a significant cancer diagnosis requiring specialized oncologic care.",
