    "longDesc": "Malignant neoplasm of unspecified site of unspecified eye",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer in the eye, but the specific location within the eye and which eye is affected are not documented or identified. It's a catch-all code used when a patient has been diagnosed with eye cancer but the medical records don't specify whether it's in the retina, iris, or other parts of the eye, or whether it's the right or left eye. This is an uncommon code in practice because most eye cancers are documented more precisely.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, ophthalmologists, and hematologist-oncologists use this code during initial diagnosis or when reviewing cases with incomplete documentation. It appears on EOB statements when patients receive cancer treatment and may be used as a temporary code until more specific imaging or pathology results clarify the exact location of the tumor.",
