    "shortDesc": "Malignant carcinoid tumor of the thymus",
    "longDesc": "Malignant carcinoid tumor of the thymus",
    "plainEnglish": "A malignant carcinoid tumor of the thymus is a rare type of cancer that starts in neuroendocrine cells (special hormone-producing cells) located in the thymus gland, which sits behind your breastbone. These tumors can grow slowly or quickly and may spread to other parts of the body, causing symptoms like chest pain, cough, or shortness of breath. Carcinoid tumors sometimes release excess hormones into the bloodstream, which can cause flushing, diarrhea, and heart palpitations.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, thoracic surgeons, and endocrinologists use this code when diagnosing and treating thymic carcinoid tumors. You will likely see this code on EOB statements if you've undergone imaging, biopsies, or surgical procedures related to thymic cancer diagnosis and treatment.",
