    "longDesc": "Malignant carcinoid tumors of other sites",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a type of cancer called a carcinoid tumor that has developed in an unusual location in the body—somewhere other than the common sites like the lungs, stomach, or intestines. Carcinoid tumors grow from neuroendocrine cells (special cells that produce hormones) and tend to grow slowly, but they are malignant, meaning they can spread to other parts of the body if not treated. These tumors may not cause noticeable symptoms early on, but over time they can cause hormonal imbalances that lead to flushing, diarrhea, wheezing, or other effects depending on which hormones they release.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and other specialists use this code when managing patients with neuroendocrine cancers in less common locations. It appears on EOB statements when patients receive cancer treatment, imaging, or biopsies for these tumors, and is typically associated with more complex and prolonged cancer care.",
