    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that started elsewhere in the body (such as the small intestine or appendix) and has spread to the peritoneum—the thin membrane lining the inside of your abdomen. Carcinoid tumors are slow-growing neuroendocrine cancers that produce hormone-like substances, which can cause symptoms like flushing, diarrhea, or abdominal pain. When these tumors metastasize (spread) to the abdominal lining, it indicates the disease has progressed and requires more aggressive treatment.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, gastroenterologists, and surgical oncologists use this code when treating patients with metastatic carcinoid disease affecting the peritoneum. This diagnosis commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, imaging studies, and surgical consultations for advanced neuroendocrine cancer.",
