    "shortDesc": "Malignant neoplasm of other specified ill-defined sites",
    "longDesc": "Malignant neoplasm of other specified ill-defined sites",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that has developed in a location in the body that is difficult to pinpoint or hasn't been clearly identified yet. The cancer cells are malignant (dangerous and spreading), but doctors haven't been able to determine the exact organ or tissue where the cancer started, possibly because it's in an unusual location or the diagnostic workup is still ongoing. This typically means additional imaging, biopsies, or specialist evaluation will be needed to find out exactly where the cancer is located.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, general practitioners, and radiologists use this code when a patient has confirmed malignant cancer but the primary site remains unknown or unspecified at the time of coding. It commonly appears as a temporary or initial diagnosis code on EOB statements and medical records when cancer is newly discovered but not yet fully classified, often leading to code changes once the primary cancer site is definitively identified.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
