    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that has spread to parts of the lungs or other breathing organs from a cancer that started somewhere else in the body. Instead of originating in the lungs themselves, cancer cells have traveled there from a primary tumor (like breast, colon, or bone cancer) and formed new tumors in the respiratory system. Patients may experience coughing, chest pain, shortness of breath, or no symptoms at all, depending on the size and location of the secondary tumors.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, pulmonologists, and internal medicine physicians use this code when managing patients with metastatic cancer affecting the lungs or other breathing organs. It commonly appears on EOB statements and medical records for patients undergoing staging, imaging, or treatment planning for advanced cancer.",
