    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that started somewhere else in the body but has spread to the brain. Unlike primary brain cancer (which originates in the brain), this cancer traveled from another organ like the lungs, breast, or skin. Patients may experience headaches, vision changes, balance problems, or neurological symptoms as the cancer affects brain tissue.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, neurologists, and neurosurgeons commonly use this code when treating patients with metastatic disease. It typically appears on EOB statements when a patient with a known cancer history undergoes brain imaging or treatment, and helps distinguish whether brain involvement is due to spread from another cancer site versus a primary brain tumor.",
