    "longDesc": "Secondary malignant neoplasm of breast",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes cancer that has spread to the breast from somewhere else in the body, rather than starting in the breast itself. When cancer cells from organs like the lungs, stomach, or other areas travel through the bloodstream or lymphatic system and settle in breast tissue, they create a secondary tumor. Patients may notice a lump, swelling, or skin changes in the breast, though symptoms depend on the size and location of the spread.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, surgical oncologists, and general surgeons use this code when a patient has metastatic cancer involving the breast. It appears in medical records when staging advanced cancer and is commonly found on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, radiation, or surgical evaluation for metastatic disease involving the breast.",
    "billable": true,
    "isNew": false,
    "isRevised": false,
