    "longDesc": "Nodular sclerosis Hodgkin lymphoma, in remission",
    "plainEnglish": "Nodular sclerosis Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of blood cancer that affects lymph nodes (small glands throughout the body that fight infection). In this variety, the cancer cells form distinctive nodules (lumps) and scar tissue within the lymph nodes. The phrase 'in remission' means the cancer has responded well to treatment and is no longer detectable—though the person will need ongoing monitoring to ensure it doesn't return.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists and hematologists use this code when documenting Hodgkin lymphoma cases in remission during follow-up visits and survivorship care. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing surveillance imaging, laboratory tests, or clinic visits related to their cancer history, and is important for tracking treatment outcomes and insurance coverage of long-term monitoring.",
