    "shortDesc": "Lymphocyte-rich Hodgkin lymphoma, spleen",
    "longDesc": "Lymphocyte-rich Hodgkin lymphoma, spleen",
    "plainEnglish": "Lymphocyte-rich Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of blood cancer where malignant cells grow in the spleen (an organ that helps fight infection). This specific subtype has an unusually high number of normal lymphocytes (immune cells) mixed in with the cancer cells, which can make it appear less aggressive than other Hodgkin lymphoma types. Patients may experience swelling of the spleen, fatigue, fever, night sweats, and weight loss.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists, hematologists, and pathologists use this code when diagnosing and treating Hodgkin lymphoma patients. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients undergoing chemotherapy, radiation, or other cancer treatments involving imaging and biopsies of the spleen.",
