    "longDesc": "Lymphocyte-rich Hodgkin lymphoma, in remission",
    "plainEnglish": "This code describes a specific type of blood cancer called Hodgkin lymphoma where the cancer cells (Reed-Sternberg cells) are surrounded by a high number of normal lymphocytes (white blood cells that fight infection). The patient has received treatment and the cancer is currently in remission, meaning there are no detectable signs of active cancer at this time. Remission doesn't necessarily mean the cancer is cured, but rather that it is not currently progressing or causing symptoms.",
    "whoUses": "Oncologists and hematologists use this code during cancer treatment follow-up visits and in remission monitoring. It commonly appears on EOB statements for patients receiving ongoing surveillance care, imaging studies, or laboratory monitoring to check for cancer recurrence, and may also appear during chemotherapy or radiation therapy claims if additional treatment is needed.",
